    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "yeah the speed of light thing is wild. it almost feels like there's some kind of hidden force or trickery happening behind the scenes to make it work like that. is there any actual theory for what's \"really\" going on, or is it just accepted as a weird rule of the universe?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The prevailing view, which is the accepted rule of the universe for now, is that it's not a hidden force in the traditional sense, but rather a fundamental property of quantum mechanics itself. The theory suggests that the particles are described by a single, shared wavefunction until a measurement forces a collapse of that shared state. Think of it like a single, giant, interconnected blob of potentiality that is only resolved when you poke one part of it. It's not that one particle is *telling* the other what to be; they are simply two aspects of one underlying reality.",
      "source": "target",
